Among these, hydrogen bonds and anion-π interactions are particularly significant. Hydrogen bonds, which occur when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom (such as oxygen or nitrogen) interacts with another electronegative atom, provide directionality and moderate strength, enabling precise molecular recognition and the stabilization of host-guest assemblies. Anion-π interactions, which involve the attraction between an anion and the electron-deficient π-system of an aromatic ring, offer a complementary mode of binding, especially for guests containing anionic groups. These interactions can enhance selectivity and binding affinity, often working synergistically with hydrogen bonds and other non-covalent forces (such as van der Waals interactions, π-π stacking, and electrostatic interactions) to drive the self-assembly of complex architectures. In supramolecular chemistry, the careful design and combination of these interactions allow for the creation of highly selective and functional host-guest systems, which are essential in applications Among these, hydrogen bonds and anion-π interactions are particularly significant. Hydrogen bonds, which occur when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom (such as oxygen or nitrogen) interacts with another electronegative atom, provide directionality and moderate strength, enabling precise molecular recognition and the stabilization of host-guest assemblies. Anion-π interactions, which involve the attraction between an anion and the electron-deficient π-system of an aromatic ring, offer a complementary mode of binding, especially for guests containing anionic groups. These interactions can enhance selectivity and binding affinity, often working synergistically with hydrogen bonds and other non-covalent forces (such as van der Waals interactions, π-π stacking, and electrostatic interactions) to drive the self-assembly of complex architectures. In supramolecular chemistry, the careful design and combination of these interactions allow for the creation of highly selective and functional host-guest systems, which are essential in applications ranging from molecular sensing to drug delivery.', 'key_concepts': ['Non-covalent interaction', 'Hydrogen bond', 'Anion-π interaction', 'Supramolecular host-guest complex', 'Molecular recognition', Among these, hydrogen bonds and anion-π interactions are particularly significant. Hydrogen bonds, which occur when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom (such as oxygen or nitrogen) interacts with another electronegative atom, provide directionality and moderate strength, enabling precise molecular recognition and the stabilization of host-guest assemblies. Anion-π interactions, which involve the attraction between an anion and the electron-deficient π-system of an aromatic ring, offer a complementary mode of binding, especially for guests containing anionic groups. These interactions can enhance selectivity and binding affinity, often working synergistically with hydrogen bonds and other non-covalent forces (such as van der Waals interactions, π-π stacking, and electrostatic interactions) to drive the self-assembly of complex architectures. In supramolecular chemistry, the careful design and combination of these interactions allow for the creation of highly selective and functional host-guest systems, which are essential in applications Among these, hydrogen bonds and anion-π interactions are particularly significant. Hydrogen bonds, which occur when a hydrogen atom covalently bonded to an electronegative atom (such as oxygen or nitrogen) interacts with another electronegative atom, provide directionality and moderate strength, enabling precise molecular recognition and the stabilization of host-guest assemblies. Anion-π interactions, which involve the attraction between an anion and the electron-deficient π-system of an aromatic ring, offer a complementary mode of binding, especially for guests containing anionic groups. These interactions can enhance selectivity and binding affinity, often working synergistically with hydrogen bonds and other non-covalent forces (such as van der Waals interactions, π-π stacking, and electrostatic interactions) to drive the self-assembly of complex architectures. In supramolecular chemistry, the careful design and combination of these interactions allow for the creation of highly selective and functional host-guest systems, which are essential in applications
